[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]CTC, the national cycling charity, was founded in 1878.  CTC has 70,000 
[normal]members and supporters, provides a range of information and legal services to cyclists, organises cycling events, and represents the interests of cyclists and cycling on issues of public policy.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]CTC’s ‘
[normal]Safety in numbers
[normal]’
[normal] campaign (
[normal]www.ctc.org..uk/campaign/safety-in-numbers
[normal]) has shown that ‘more’ and ‘safer’ cycling can 
[normal]and should
[normal] go hand in hand, as well as calling for the actions needed to ensure that they do.  CTC’s ongoing 
[normal]‘
[normal]Road Justice
[normal]’
[normal] 
[normal]campaign (
[normal]www.roadjustice.org.uk
[normal]) is highlighting the inadequacies of the responses to bad driving from the police, 
[normal]prosecutors and the courts, while calling for action to improve these.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]CTC played a key role 
[normal]in shaping the Times newspaper’s 8-point ‘Cities fit for cycling’ manifesto
[normal], and the subsequent parliamentary ‘Get Britain Cycling’ inquiry and report
[normal], whose 18 recommendations we 
[normal]strongly 
[normal]endorse.  
[normal]CTC’s President, the broadcaster Jon Snow, gave evidenc
[normal]e both at the Commons Transport Committee’s original inquiry on the Government’s road safety strategy
[normal], and the ‘Get Britain Cycling’ inquiry
[normal], emphasising the importance of ‘leadership’ in order to get Britain cycling.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In response, the Prime Minister has
[normal] now publicly stated his ambition to launch a “Cycling revolution”.  The Government is now drafting a Cycle Delivery Plan, aimed at fulfilling this ambition.  CTC is represented on the steering group providing high-level input to this Plan, and recently ho
[normal]sted 3 days of discussions with Department for Transport (DfT) officials
[normal] to discuss proposals.  We also have regular dialogue with officials from DfT and other departments or governmental bodies, including the Highways Agency.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Cycling is essenti
[normal]ally a safe activity, causing little risk either to cyclists themselves or to other road users.  Its health benefits far outweigh the risks involved, i.e. despite those risks, cycling significantly increases one
[normal]’
[normal]s average life expectancy.  Moreover, there 
[normal]is good evidence that cyclists gain from ‘safety in numbers’, with cycling typically becoming safer as cycle use increases.  In other words, more and safer cycling can, and should, go hand in hand.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Cycle safety is nonetheless a good deal worse in Britain 
[normal]than in many neighbouring continental 
[normal]countries.  Despite its health and other benefits, people in Britain are deterred from cycling (or from allowing our children to do so) by both the actual and perceived risks involved.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To maximise the health, economic
[normal], environmental and other benefits of more and safer cycling, the focus of action nationally and locally needs to be on removing those actual and perceived risks: unsafe road and junction designs, traffic volumes and speeds, irresponsible driving (and a le
[normal]gal system that fails to respond adequately to this), and lorries.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Cycle training also 
[normal]plays
[normal] an important role, not only in giving would-be cyclists of all ages
[normal] 
[normal]the confidence and skills needed to cycle safely and legally, but also 
[normal]in improving
[normal] driving st
[normal]andards
[normal] 
[normal]as part of the driver training process, particularly for drivers of lorries and other large vehicles.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q1: Is cycling safe?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Cycling is not an especially risky activity. On average, 1 
[normal]cyclist is killed
[normal] on Britain’s roads for every 26
[normal] m
[normal]illion miles travelled by cycle,
[normal] 
[normal]equating
[normal] 
[normal]roughly to 
[normal]1 cycle fatality for 
[normal]every 10
[normal]00 times cycled round the world.
[normal] You are 
[normal]about as
[normal] 
[normal]un
[normal]likely to be killed in a mile of cycling 
[normal]as 
[normal]a mile of walking
[normal], and 
[normal]le
[normal]ss likely 
[normal]to be injured in an hour of 
[normal]cycling
[normal] than an hour of 
[normal]gardening
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]More
[normal] information on the low risks of cycling are in CTC’s 
[normal]‘R
[normal]oad safety
[normal]’
[normal] campaigns briefing
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]By contrast, the health benefits of cycling are vast.  A person who cycles regularly (but not strenuously) in mid-adulthood 
[normal]typically enjoys a level of fitness equivalent to someone 10 years younger, and has a life expectancy two years above the average. 
[normal] 
[normal]It has been estimated that, thanks to these extra life-years, 
[normal]the 
[normal]health 
[normal]benefits of cycling 
[normal]outweigh the risks involved by around 20:1, a figure now endorsed by the UK Government.
[normal]  
[normal]A population-wide study in Copenhagen found that, compared with those who 
[normal]cycled regularly to work, people who did not do so had a 39% higher mortality rate, regardless of whether or not they sometimes took part in other physical activities at other times.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Although cycling is relatively (but
[normal] not exceptionally) risky for the user compared with most
[normal] 
[normal]other transport modes, the opposite is true if you consider how little risk cyclists impose on
[normal] 
[normal]other people.  In 2012, 98
[normal]% of killed or seriously injured (KSI) pedestrians in urban areas
[normal] 
[normal](i.e. where
[normal] pedestrians are most likely to be) resulted from collisions with motor vehicles.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A CTC analysis of Department for Transport (DfT) data for 2005-07
[normal] revealed that, per urban
[normal] mile travelled (excluding motorways, where cyclists and pedestrians are prohibited), cars are 2.3 times more likely than cycles to be involved in a pedestrian injury, and 3.2 times as likely 
[normal]to be involved in a pedestrian fatality.  The ratios of danger p
[normal]resented to pedestrians and
[normal] cyclists by each class of vehicle are displayed 
[normal]in the following table
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]CTC’s ‘Safety in numbers’
[normal] booklet
[normal] 
[normal]provides f
[normal]urther information on the low risks of cycling to other road users.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]13
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is also good evidence that increased cycle use can be good for the safety of cyclists themselves –
[normal] i.e., that cyclists gain from ‘
[normal]Safety in Numbers
[normal]’
[normal].  This can be seen both from international comparisons, from 
[normal]trends over time in both Britain and the Netherlands, and from CTC’s own comparison of cycle use and cyclists’ safety in different parts of Britain.
[normal]&#xa0;
